{
  "text": "One of such species is Trichia papillata Adamonyt\u0117. This species was described in Lithuania in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Fruiting bodies formed during cultivation in moist chambers on the hare (Lepus sp.) and roe deer (Capreolus capreolus) dung. Information about finding of T. papillata in Taiwan was published in 2007 (liu et al., 2007) . In that study, one specimen was collected in Wenshan Botanical Gardens of National Taiwan University, and two more were obtained in moist chamber cultures on the 43rd and 74th day of incubation. In both cases, fruiting bodies formed on leaf litter and small twigs (liu et al., 2007) .",
